{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:06:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19265"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19265"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.08,0.11,0.05,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107539"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11999"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90009"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1207"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8813"},{"type":"tags","id":"8888"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107539"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of increasing eye irritation, itching, and mucoid discharge. She reports her contact lenses have become increasingly uncomfortable to wear and often become displaced. She has worn soft contact lenses daily for the past five years without previous issues. She has no other medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/6 in both eyes. Eversion of the upper eyelids reveals multiple elevated papillae greater than 0.3mm in diameter on the superior tarsal conjunctiva. There is mild conjunctival injection but no corneal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical mast cell stabiliser","Topical corticosteroids","Topical antibiotics","Switching to rigid gas permeable lenses","Cessation of contact lens wear"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of giant papillary conjunctivitis (GPC), a condition commonly associated with contact lens wear that it is also known as contact lens-induced papillary conjunctivitis. The characteristic finding is papillae greater than 0.3mm on the superior tarsal conjunctiva, along with symptoms of irritation, itching, and mucoid discharge. The history of long wearing time may increase the risk of developing GPC. Other risk factors include poor lens hygiene, infrequent replacement of lens and use of non-disposable lenses. Most causes are associated with contact lens wears but GPC may be triggered by other mechanical traumas to the conjunctiva.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECessation of contact lens wear\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management given that she has mild-moderate symptoms. This removes the mechanical irritant that is triggering the inflammatory response. Most patients show significant improvement within weeks of discontinuing contact lens use, and may be able to re-start using contact lenses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical mast cell stabilisers\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in managing the allergic component of GPC, but they should be considered as an adjunctive treatment after contact lens cessation. The cause of GPC is unknown but it is not a true allergy to the contact lenses but is rather considered an immunological reaction to it. Topical mast cell stabilisers can be particularly useful if symptoms persist despite lens removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E may be effective in severe cases but are not first-line therapy due to their potential side effects, including increased intraocular pressure and cataract formation. They should be reserved for cases that don\u0027t respond to more conservative measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to rigid gas permeable lenses\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the initial management step. It is likely to cause the patient similar issues with wearing her contact lenses. While some patients may eventually be able to return to contact lens wear with a different lens type, this should only be considered after the condition has resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as GPC is not caused by bacterial infection. The condition is primarily an inflammatory/allergic response to mechanical irritation from contact lens wear.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Giant papillary conjunctivitis is commonly associated with contact lens wear and requires cessation of contact lens use as first-line management","Papillae greater than 0.3mm on the superior tarsal conjunctiva are diagnostic of giant papillary conjunctivitis","Treatment involves addressing both the mechanical irritation and the allergic component of the condition"],"references":["Kenny S, Tye Cooper, Johnson D, Kheirkhah A. Giant papillary conjunctivitis: A review.  The Ocular Surface. 2020: 18 (3).  Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1542012420300604","Roh H et al. Giant Papillary Conjunctivitis Caused by a Fibroepithelial Polyp of the Lower Eyelid. The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology: In Practice. 2023: 11 (6).  Available at: https://www.jaci-inpractice.org/article/S2213-2198(23)00349-5/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90009"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19265"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90009"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T09:03:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T09:04:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11999"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107539"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations